PatientLevelPrediction v5.0.0

2022-02-02

Introduction

In PatientLevelPrediction v5.0.0 there has been changes to the way the data are extracted, the process to develop the model and the output objects. This document will describe the new code and describe the output objects.

For this document you will need to install the Eunomia package and the latest PatientLevelPrediction package by executing:

## if you do not have devtools you will need it:
#install.packages('devtools')

## install Eunomia as this is used in the examples
# devtools::install_github('ohdsi/Eunomia')

## install PatientLevelPrediction
#devtools::install_github('ohdsi/PatientLevelPrediction',  ref = 'issue242')

To view the latest PatientLevelPrediction code see GitHub Link

Code Structure Diagram

The interactions between the key functions in PatientLevelPrediction v5.0.0 are shown below.

PatientLevelPrediction v5.0.0 code framework

Data Extraction

The function used to extract the data is still named getPlpData() however the input to this function has changed. getPlpData() now requires three inputs:

The three inputs into getPlpData()
inputs descriptions
databaseDetails An object of class databaseDetails containing the connection, schema and table names to the OMOP CDM database and database containing the cohorts.
covariateSettings An object of class covariateSettings containing the settings for extracting the covariates (or a list of covariateSettings).
restrictPlpDataSettings An object of class restrictPlpDataSettings containing inclusions criteria for the target cohort that is implemented during data extraction (such as data sampling, restricting to indexes occuring between certain dates, minimum prior observation at index and whether to restrict to first cohort period if a person is in the target cohort multiple times).

Example Code To Extract Data

The databaseDetails object is created using the function PatientLevelPrediction::createDatabaseDetails(). It specifies the connectionDetails to the OMOP CDM you wish to extract data from as well as the schema, a shareable name for the OMOP CDM database and schema and table names where the target and outcome cohorts have been generated. To demonstrate this we will use the Eunomia package.

# set up the connection
connectionDetails <- Eunomia::getEunomiaConnectionDetails()

# create the database
Eunomia::createCohorts(
  connectionDetails = connectionDetails, 
  cdmDatabaseSchema = 'main', 
  cohortDatabaseSchema = 'main', 
  cohortTable = 'cohort'
  )

databaseDetails <- PatientLevelPrediction::createDatabaseDetails(
  connectionDetails = connectionDetails, 
  cdmDatabaseSchema = 'main', 
  cdmDatabaseName = 'Eunomia', 
  cohortDatabaseSchema = 'main', 
  cohortTable = 'cohort', 
  cohortId = 4,
  outcomeDatabaseSchema = 'main', 
  outcomeTable = 'cohort', 
  outcomeId = 3,
  cdmVersion = 5
  )

The covariateSettings objects can be created using the function FeatureExtraction::createCovariateSettings() or PatientLevelPrediction::createCohortCovariateSettings() or custom functions can be written to specify what covariates to extract. For example, to add standard covariates from FeatureExtraction that consist of age in 5-year buckets, gender and conditions/drugs using the era tables and vocabulary hierarchy that occur from 365 days until 1 day prior to the target index date:

covariateSettings <- FeatureExtraction::createCovariateSettings(
  useDemographicsGender = T, 
  useDemographicsAgeGroup = T, 
  useConditionGroupEraLongTerm = T, 
  useDrugGroupEraLongTerm = T, 
  endDays = -1, 
  longTermStartDays = -365
)

Finally, the restrictPlpDataSettings object is created using the PatientLevelPrediction::createRestrictPlpDataSettings(). This enables a user to specify any inclusions that can be done when downloading the data. This means it will not be possible to investigate the sensitivity of these inclusion criteria unless new data are extracted, but these settings can make data extraction quicker. To restrict to patients in the target population to those satisfying:

  1. index date between Jan 1st 2000 and Jan 1st 2020
  2. restrict to first occurrence in the target cohort
  3. >= 30 days observation in database prior to index

then we can use the following settings:

restrictPlpDataSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createRestrictPlpDataSettings(
  studyStartDate = '20000101',
  studyEndDate = '20200101',
  firstExposureOnly = T, 
  washoutPeriod = 30
)

# issue with studyStartDate/studyEndDate
restrictPlpDataSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createRestrictPlpDataSettings(
  firstExposureOnly = T, 
  washoutPeriod = 30
)

Putting this together, we can extract the plpData by executing:

plpData <- PatientLevelPrediction::getPlpData(
  databaseDetails = databaseDetails, 
  covariateSettings = covariateSettings, 
  restrictPlpDataSettings = restrictPlpDataSettings
  )

plpData Structure

After successfully executing PatientLevelPrediction::getPlpData the object of class plpData is returned. This is a list containing the following components:

  • cohorts: a data.frame with the columns ‘rowId’, ‘subjectId’, ‘cohortId’, ‘cohortStartDate’, ‘daysFromObsStart’, ‘daysToCohortEnd’, ‘daysToObsEnd’, ‘ageYear’, ‘gender’

  • outcomes: a data.frame with the columns ‘rowId’, ‘outcomeId’, ‘daysToEvent’

  • covariateData: an object of class CovariateData containing:

    • covariates: an andromeda object with the columns: ‘rowId’, ‘covariateId’, ‘covariateValue’
    • analysisRef: information about the analysisIds in the covariateRef
    • covariateRef: information about the covariates

  • metaData: a list containing the databaseDetails (with the connection details removed), covariateSettings and restrictPlpDataSettings used to extract the data

Useful exercise: Run the example code above and play with the plpData object.

Note: The structure of plpData has not changed in v5.0.0, but the metaData object has been updated to store the new input settings.

Model development and internal validation

The function use to develop the model and calculate the interval validation is still named runPlp() however the inputs have changed and the object returned by runPlp has also changed. runPlp()` now requires 13 inputs:

The inputs into runPlp()
inputs descriptions
plpData An object of class plpData created using getPlpData().
outcomeId The cohort_definition_id for the outcome you want to predict.
analysisId A unique identifier for the analysis
analysisName A name for the analysis
populationSettings An object of class populationSettings created using the createStudyPopulationSettings(). This specifies how the outcome labels are generated (the time at risk settings) and any exclusion criteria to apply after data extraction.
splitSettings An object of class splitSettings created using createDefaultSplitSetting(). This specifies how the split the data into test/train/folds.
sampleSettings (optional) An object of class sampleSettings created using createSampleSettings() or by a custom function. This can be used to over sample or under sample the patients in the data.
featureEngineeringSettings (optional) An object of class featureEngineeringSettings create using createFeatureEngineeringSettings() or a custom function. This can be used to do feature selection or to create new features in the data.
preprocessSettings An object of class preprocessSettings created using createPreprocessSettings(). This specifies whether to normalize the features and whether to remove reduntant or rare features.
modelSettings An object of class modelSettings created using one of the set functions or using a custom function. This specifies the machine learning algorithm to use to learn the prediction model and the hyper-parameters, plus the search strategy.
logSettings An object of class logSettings created using createLogSettings(). This specifies the logging settings, such as verbosity.
executeSettings An object of class executeSettings created using createExecuteSettings(). This specifies what part of the framework to apply (e.g., whether to do sampling or feature engineering).
saveDirectory The directory to save the model and performance results

Example Code To Develop Model and Internally Validate

For this example we will develop a logistic regression model using the setLassoLogisticRegression() model settings to predict the outcome occuring 1 day after index until 2 years after index in patients who have not had the outcome prior to index:

# create a population setting that labels people as having the outcome if
# they had the outcome recorded between 1 day after index and 730 days after
# index.  Remove people who had the outcome anytime prior (lookback 99999 days)
# and only include the earlier cohort entry (if a person is in cohort multiple times)
populationSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createStudyPopulationSettings(
  binary = T, 
  includeAllOutcomes = F, # best practice showed this causes bias
  firstExposureOnly = T, 
  washoutPeriod = 180, 
  removeSubjectsWithPriorOutcome = T, 
  priorOutcomeLookback = 99999, 
  requireTimeAtRisk = F, 
  riskWindowStart = 1, 
  startAnchor = 'cohort start', 
  riskWindowEnd = 365*2, 
  endAnchor = 'cohort start' 
)

# split into 25% test and 75% training data, use 3-fold cross validation
# random split but keep outcome rate the same in test/train
splitSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createDefaultSplitSetting(
  testFraction = 0.25, 
  trainFraction = 0.75, 
  splitSeed = 123, 
  nfold = 3, 
  type = 'stratified'
  )

# do no sampling
sampleSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createSampleSettings(
  type = 'none'
  )

# do no feature engineering
featureEngineeringSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createFeatureEngineeringSettings(
  type = 'none'
  )

# normalize features and remove any redundant ones
preprocessSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createPreprocessSettings(
  minFraction = 0, 
  normalize = T, 
  removeRedundancy = T
  )

logSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createLogSettings(verbosity = 'INFO')
## Use timeStamp: TRUE
executeSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::createExecuteSettings(
  runSplitData = T, 
  runSampleData = F, 
  runfeatureEngineering = F, 
  runPreprocessData = T, 
  runModelDevelopment = T, 
  runCovariateSummary = T
  )

# use default LASSO logistic regression 
modelSettings <- PatientLevelPrediction::setLassoLogisticRegression()

runPlp <- PatientLevelPrediction::runPlp( 
  plpData = plpData, 
  outcomeId = 3, 
  analysisId = 'plp_demo', 
  analysisName = 'Demonstrating the plp v5.0.0', 
  populationSettings = populationSettings, 
  splitSettings = splitSettings, 
  sampleSettings = sampleSettings, 
  featureEngineeringSettings = featureEngineeringSettings, 
  preprocessSettings = preprocessSettings, 
  modelSettings = modelSettings, 
  logSettings = logSettings, 
  executeSettings = executeSettings, 
  saveDirectory = file.path(tempdir(), 'plp')
  )

runPlp Structure

If the function runPlp() executes successfully, then an object of class runPlp is returned. An object of class runPlp is a list containing:

  • executionSummary: a list with details about the computer used to run the code, the execution date and versions of R and PatientLevelPrediction. This is useful when debugging issues.
  • analysisRef: a list containing the analysisId and analysisName
  • prediction: a data.frame including the columns: ‘rowId’, ‘value’, ‘evaluationType’
  • covariateSummary: a data.frame with summary details about each of the candidate features (this is a characterization).
  • performanceEvaluation: a list of performance objects (these are used to generate the performance plots)
  • model: an object of class plpModel (this is described below)

In the sections below the prediction object, covariateSummary, performanceEvaluation and model objects are presented for the example using Eunomia.

model Structure

The model is an object of class plpModel. The class plpModel structure has changed in PatientLevelPrediction v5.0.0. The new plpModel class is a list with the following structure:

  • Model: a pointer to where the model is saved or a list with the model

  • settings: a list containing:

    • plpDataSettings: the plpDataSettings settings input to getPlpData()

    • covariateSettings: the covariateSettings input to getPlpData()

    • populationSettings: the populationSettings

    • featureEngineering: the featureEngineeringSettings

    • tidyCovariates the output of preprocessSettings

      • populationSize: integer
      • deletedRedundantCovariateIds: vector of covariateIds
      • deletedInfrequentCovariateIds: vector of covariateIds (can be large)
      • normFactors: tibble with columns: covariateId and maxValue (can be large)

    • requireDenseMatrix – logical

    • modelSettings - the modelSettings

    • splitSettings - the splitSettings

    • sampleSettings - the sampleSettings

  • trainDetails: a list with:

    • analysisId: the analysisId that was input

    • analysisSource: (not currently in)

    • cdmDatabaseSchema: the cdmDatabaseSchema from the databaseDetails

    • outcomeId: the outcomeId from the populationSettings

    • cohortId: the cohortId from the databaseDetails

    • attrition: a data.frame with the number of people remaining after each exclusion criteria in the study population creation

    • trainingTime: time taken to develop the model

    • trainingDate: the date the model was developed

    • hyperParamSearch: a data.frame with the hyper-parameter search details

  • covariateImportance: a data.frame with 7 columns (can be large): This tells you the column id for each covariateId

The plpModel must also have the attributes:

  • predictionFunction: A character specifying the function used to make prediction with this model
  • modelType: either ‘binary’/‘survival’
  • saveType: either ‘RtoJson’/‘file’/‘xgboost’ (used when saving the model)

Exercise: execute runPlp() with your choice of settings. If it works explore the results. If it fails, let me know so we can fix it, we did this tutorial to hack the code and find some bugs…

Built in preprocessing functions

Here are the list of the current built in functions for the sampling, feature engineering and data splitting. These can all be customized (there are documents in the PatientLevelPrediction vignettes folder).

The functions that are in the package
functionName type descriptions
createDefaultSplitSetting() Splitting Does the outcome stratified, by subject or temporal split test/train sets with cross validation
createFeatureEngineeringSettings() Feature Engineering Currently does nothing
createUnivariateFeatureSelection() Feature Engineering Picks features that are most correlated to the outcome. This is useful if using Naive Bayes as the model.
createRandomForestFeatureSelection() Feature Engineering Applies a random forest and picks the variables with the highest feature importance. This is useful if using random forest as the model.
createSampleSettings() Sampling Currently gives the option to do none or under sample
